column1: 324001;instagram;2018-09-30 15:56:12;FALSE;"sometimes you have to teach yourself how to be brave. i normally don’t get sucked into what’s trending but being a advocate for women empowerment
column3: human rights come right along with that. to hear people say why do victims wait so long to say something...being brave is learned behavior.

column1: and even while being brave we have to prove you’re still brave when combatted with questions
column2: with judgment with speculation and people who doubt you’re telling the truth.

column1: you may not even realize you’re choosing to be brave in the moment.
it may not occur to that the actions equate a certain hero/heroine act in the midst of the turmoil.
sometimes people have to point it out and say wow! that was really brave of you to do/ to say that.
bravery is a muscle. the more you do it the more it grows. but also sometimes being brave is all we know. sometimes having a child
column4: a horrible act brings a certain bravery out of you unbeknownst to you until you’re faced to make a decision to speak

column1: bravery is scary af. bravery is tiring af.
many of us are still learning that. every single day. in and through the fire
and what a lesson to be learned. cause not everyone will flex when the time comes to use the muscle.
so when you’re choosing to be brave know that you’re also dope af. so thank you.

column1: to the humans reading this: there are private messages going out to women to change their profile pics to a black screen to teach men what the world would be like without women. this is the most ridiculous behavior i’ve witnessed this year. women we can do better than this.

column2: men and women have had some sort of sexual trauma in our life happen to us. let me repeat this to you; men and women have had some sort of sexual trauma in our life happen to us. we are given that experience to learn from. the lesson is not given to us to harbor and suffer our entire life from.

column1: i see so many people posting on social media about their sexual trauma and i’m proud of each one of you for releasing that trauma and talking about it.
now choose the direction your life will go from here on out. i encourage you to take time for yoga

column1: 324022;instagram;2018-09-30 15:36:00;FALSE;"(1/2) he and i went to a casual party last night. there were only a few people when we got there
column2: and i was fine. i was nervous because i wanted to make a good first impression to his friends
column3: but i was happy to be with him. and then one by one
column4: more men came into this tiny little house until there were eight or nine of them. ⁣⁣⁣⁣

column2: i felt like i couldn’t breathe. the room was spinning and my head was pounding and i felt like i was going to hurl and i wanted to run. i wanted to run as far away as i could. and it took my brain awhile to catch up with my body
column3: but i realized that i was having a dr. christine blasey ford moment. i needed two front doors. i needed three. or four. or twelve.⁣⁣⁣

column1: and it hit me like a ton of bricks — i was run over by a freight train and i realized that i was terrified that they were going to do what you did to me. and they all seemed nice and no one was inappropriate
column2: and he stayed by my side all night and laughed with his friends and played video games and kissed me every chance he got
column3: but i was stiff and silent. i remembered how you assaulted me
column4: remembered how other men before you abused and assaulted me and made me terrified of existence itself. ⁣⁣⁣i remember. ⁣⁣⁣i will always remember. ⁣⁣

column1: and i don’t know how long we were there — longer than i wanted to be
column2: because i was too proud and embarrassed and scared to admit that i was terrified of these seemingly kind men. every time someone tried to get me to play a video game and i said no
column3: they asked again. they were kind and encouraging; they thought i was just afraid of losing and tried to ease my embarrassment. but that wasn’t it
column4: and all i wanted to scream was “no
column5: i can’t sit that close to you
column6: i can’t focus on this stupid fucking game because i was raped and i am petrified of being alone with all of these men in a house that has only one front door.” ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣

column1: and that’s what you did to me. ⁣⁣

column1: 324049;instagram;2018-09-30 15:08:05;TRUE;;"sharing a post from my very dear friend. i think
column3: we are all triggered by the news these days. but for those with abuse histories
column4: this past week was likely to bring up flashbacks and anxiety.

column1: my advice to those who may be having a difficult time: it’s okay to take a break from media and technology.
sometimes just hitting the off button can enable your system to recharge and allow you to exhale.
#edwontletu see how you weren’t to blame
column3: and you deserved to be heard! i’ve wanted to post something about this topic for awhile
column4: but it felt too close to home. but
column5: i’ve had enough! we continue to shame and blame victims. we continue to ignore the facts. sexual assault is the most under reported crime. 63% of rape victims never report it to the police. as a therapist i’ve seen countless clients blame themselves for their assaults
column6: assuming that they: “should have known better”
column10: i gotta say the stigma is in no way fabricated. my own family member i confided in never took my assault seriously and continued a relationship with the perpetrator. years later when i questioned her response she literally said to me “that’s what men do”. we live in a world where victims are silenced
column11: perpetrators get slaps on the wrist (if anything at all)
column12: and we perpetuate the cognitive distortions victims tell themselves. these distortions leave them at risk to be re- victimized and to develop ptsd

column3: brings all the big questions of misogyny and sexism in the best way i can think of - through bridge and co’s trip to a retro screening of saturday night fever. was it wrong then? is it wrong now? should things be re-examined in the new - more woke - light of day? a great extract to get you thinking and laughing this sunday. must read for men and women alike.

column1: 324094;instagram;2018-09-30 14:56:02;FALSE;"in light of what's happening in our country right now i thought i would post the photos from a photoshoot i did relating to a story a close friend told me.
she was 16 years old and 2 men raped her. she wasn't drunk
column4: and it wasn't just ""boys being boys"". when she told her sister she told her to ""just forget about it"". so she tried
column5: because if her own sister didn't understand why would anybody else? she pushed it down deep and didn't tell a soul. she suffered from depression
column7: and drug use through her teen years. just 2 years ago she told me about this horrific story. she suffered for so long keeping this to herself
column8: and when i did this photo shoot in honor of her story
column9: she told me she felt a weight lifted off her shoulders.

column1: 324097;instagram;2018-09-30 14:56:59;FALSE;"i am tearful as i write this. i’ve been crying all week. at my desk at work
column2: in my bed alone and in the arms of my amazing friends. the events of this week have brought back traumatic memories that i’ve pushed into the deepest darkest depths of my mind. i feel empowered to say that i too am a victim of sexual assault. i kept this a secret until about 2 years ago when i was diagnosed with bipolar disorder and started going to therapy.
i was afraid and i thought i would be blamed for what happened to me. not by my family
column3: they are loving and amazing. they have been and always will be my #1 fans in life. i know that if i had spoken up they would have pulled me from that situation immediately. but i was too young to understand what happened and as i grew up i taught myself to toughen up. because worse has happened to other women
column4: and it could have been worse for me right?

column2: i still don’t understand and i’m still afraid. i’m anxious and i overthink every situation
column3: plan out every interaction and think of every scenario. i walked into a party last night and the first thing i did was scan the room. i knew where the exits were
column4: and i made sure i got a look at everyone in the room. i do this everywhere i go.

column1: i don’t do this because i’m trying to find the cutest woman at the bar. i do this because i am fearful
column2: and anxious and constantly worried about what could happen to me or my friends. no one should live their lives like this.

column1: i know there aren’t any details about what happened to me in this message. i’m not ready to share with anyone who doesn’t already know. but i hope this empowers someone else to seek help. to my friends and fellow survivors. you are worthy
column2: you are loved and your experience is valid.

column2: it can uproot us or create new roots. neither better than the other. in the past i’ve uprooted by choice.. this time i’m facing the challenges as options to root into my life’s purpose. to expand my support base
column3: to make strength where there was once weakness. connecting to a deeper truth and acceptance
column4: to continue down this journey to save the world from textile pollution. #truth

column1: i don’t run my businesses to “do it all” i don’t miss out on friendships so i can paint my nails and enjoy a relaxing evening in solitude. i have chosen to work as hard as i do because i know the planet is dying. i know that every pound i save is helping the planet in a small way. it’s urgent and this is my choice. .
it’s been a challenging yet equally gratifying these past few months with the growth of my companies
column2: services & physical expansion. failures learned never to repeat and new bridges crossed with a bright future ahead. all while loneliness and being misunderstood
column5: continue to sneak up in the times where i should feel victorious. i knew i needed to be proactive to conquer current and future obstacles of negative self-talk beyond my self-care efforts.

column1: i researched groups that would surround me with like-minded women in business. thank goodness for @womeninrural and @womenwhostartup harvesting options for me to expand my support and educational channels.
thank goodness for @timferriss podcasts and my new employees that accept me as i am and will help me grow as a boss and individual
column2: i have so much to learn from them.

324131;instagram;2018-09-30 14:37:44;FALSE;“the first catcalling experience that i distinctly remember was when i was about 12 or 13. i was leaving my grandparents house late afternoon after a day of swimming. i was dressed in casual shorts and a tank top. the house across the street was being built and was full of construction workers. as i walked out to the car to leave i began hearing whistles and smooching sounds. boos and hollers as well. they made kissy noises and shouted “hey baby.” i

column1: 324146;instagram;2018-09-30 14:41:58;FALSE;"i have several #metoo stories.  i was young and insecure and easy prey. all of the horrible things that happened to me sent me on a downward spiral of alcoholism
column3: depression and codependency. at some point along the way i decided that enough was enough. i have 2 daughters and i wanted to be a good role model for them. i quit drinking and began to work through some of the negative self talk.

column1: i picked up tools along the way and discovered that there are many different paths to healing. this is why i created the 1st wise women retreat. you see
column3: although there are many different paths
column4: there is one thing that is certain. we get stronger and heal together. we need community. this is the basis of all 12 step meetings. support from others who understand. we need our tribe so that we can lift each other up and catch each other when we fall.

column2: honor the cycles of the moon and most of all
october 5th and/or 6th as we host another event at atmalogy
column3: teachings of the goddess kali! click on gaiasisterhood.org under goddess gatherings

column2: we are co-facilitating and event with freedom folk and soul. dia de los muertos
column3: honoring our ancestors with chili dinner
column4: shamanic breathwork and shrine making! register at gaiasisterhood.org click on gaia circle.

column1: masculinity is not toxic. i know this can feel counter intuitive for many of you nowadays but is is not. -

column3: we are pressured from a young age to conform to a toxic culture of masculinity that does irreparable damages across the board. on a daily basis. and it has been going on for generations. it is time for men to step up.

column2: discovering what masculinity is and pealing off the layers of the lies we are feeding boys has been transformative
column4: challenging and liberating. it has been everything but comfortable. it is incredibly uncomfortable.

column2: i share again this amazing piece of wisdom from my friend mark greene @remakingmanhood. dear men
column3: this inner work and outer of work of challenging this toxic culture is necessary and it is on us. this is an inside job. this is an uncomfortable inside job. but this is a necessary job. do it for her. do it for yourself. do it for the world.

column1: 324173;instagram;2018-09-30 14:18:25;FALSE;"it’s hard not to judge other by what they choose share with the external world. we see what is presented on social media and we believe that people do live in their perfect world. we believe they have something we can’t attain
column2: we believe their lives are better than ours
column3: we begin to believe that somehow we are less than. .

column1: today i want to remind you that despite what someone chooses to share
column2: they also may be fighting a battle you can’t see. that girl that is laughing so hard in her pictures may also be crying herself to sleep at night. .

column1: before making assumptions or believing everything we see
column2: let’s take a step back and remember that “we don’t know what we don’t know” .

column1: 324183;instagram;2018-09-30 14:22:00;FALSE;"after seeing so many brave survivors come forward recently
column2: i feel inspired to finally share my story; knowing that i have a lot of former students and younger cousins following me here
column3: and that’s all the more reason to share. (tw for sexual assault ahead)
i was sexually assaulted by someone i knew and trusted
column4: who betrayed my trust in the worst possible way.  close to a decade later
column8: while my attacker has yet to experience a single consequence for what he did to me. .

column1: there are many reasons i chose not to report the assault
column2: the main one being that i just wanted it to go away and push it to the farthest corner of my mind and forget about it.  but after watching dr. ford’s brave testimony
column3: i’ve realized that i can’t ignore it anymore.  i carry this baggage with me for the rest of my life
column4: but i am done letting it define me.  like my shirt says

column1: i hope that by sharing my truth
column2: other sexual assault survivors will feel less alone. even if you choose not to report it
column3: but please don’t hesitate to reach out to your support system.  you’re not alone ❤️

column1: 324190;instagram;2018-09-30 01:01:07;FALSE;"sugar and spice and everything nice - that's what the old rhyme assured me i was made of. it didn't feel like it though. for me - and more friends than i can bear to count - girlhood was made of secrets and shame and taking the blame.

i am bone tired of victims of abuse and assault being obliged to lay out the terrible details of our traumas in what seems like an increasingly futile attempt to make the general public realize what a widespread problem this is.

column3: maybe six. and had already been raped (not by the man in the picture). in the second
column4: i am nine and have already attempted suicide to escape from sexual abuse by an extended family member who was well respected in his community and a cub scout leader.

column2: i am thirteen. about two years deep into aggressive cat calls and being followed by strange adult men
column3: and groping disguised as hugging from familiar adult men.

column2: i am sixteen and two months away from an attempted rape by a family friend in his forties. i told my family what happened the night it happened
column3: and was kicked out of my house for three days after being called both a liar and a whore.

column2: i am seventeen and really fucking high. i was doing somersaults up and down that hallway. i didn't want sex
column3: but i was too high to keep it from happening. the person taking the picture knew that and gave me drugs for free for that exact reason.

column1: and that's all before reaching adulthood.

column1: and just so there is no confusion about where i stand...

column1: 324195;instagram;2018-09-30 13:55:16;FALSE;"my art space....this week has been so full of friends in need. i spent the better part with one friend who was having a rough time with her fibromyalgia flaring up and her mom having a heart attack. then i learn another friend was raped. i sat with her at the er to do a rape kit and then afterwards to keep her company. then another friend is having a really hard time and feeling worthless. i spent time with her and took her out for a while to the river to help clear her head. so today i finally am taking time for me and my art. i got all my supplies. 😁

i love the circle of women i run with...there’s a gentle fierceness that is being expressed as we own our voices and speak the truth.
this is a quintessential era we are living in as we shed our collective stories of the past....literally uncovering buried wounds so that they can be healed.
this is the “work” we came here to do starting first with ourselves and rippling out all the to women - and men we touch. it is time to heal. we deserve it. the planet deserves it.
allow yourself to awaken and move from that place to action...not from a place of fear but from an elevated frequency of infinite possibility. .

column1: this is a problematic letter. problematic because it's both an apology and a rally cry. problematic because in this society it's always innocent until proven guilty
column2: unless the accused is a woman demanding justice. because what you've been through
column3: is something most woman have been through at least once in their life

column1: this is a problematic letter because the world keeps telling you to raise your voice
column2: but then stifles you the moment you open your mouth. because the society will call you an attention whore every time you call them out on their pervertedness. because when a man molests a woman
column3: it becomes the woman's responsibility to prove her claim instead of the man's responsibility to defend his innocence.

column1: this is a problematic letter because a man is either too young for his career to be ruined or too old for his reputation to be soiled. if he's rich she's a gold digger
column2: if he's famous she's a power hungry bitch
column3: if he's influential she's just crying wolf
column4: if he's neither she's just another vengeful feminist. this is a problematic letter because there's no justice
column6: there's no trial. it's all a matter of inconvenience which shall either be forgotten or denied
column7: never given the importance it deserves.

column3: you've persevered. despite the threats you haven't shrunk away from demanding the truth come out. despite the indifference you've not lost all hope.

column2: but it is also one to remind you
column3: don't stop asking for justice because the world will never stop asking for anything less from you. this is to remind you that your voice might be the one which opens a floodgate of fearlessness. this is to tell you to keep your voice raised
column4: and promise you it'll never be alone in this fight.

it’s been hard this weekend disconnecting from everything that is happening in the world. i keep trying to find words to explain what seems to be something that a lot of people don’t understand about being a woman
column3: about your existence being determined by what you can offer men from the moment you’re born; your worth diminished to how well you can perform this role as a woman. but if far more eloquent people have explained it and people still don’t understand
column4: how much luck am i going to have? people believe what they want and the truth has nothing to do with it. i fear i am losing the idealist in me
column5: the one i swore i would protect as older and wiser people warned me i would lose her as i became older and wiser myself. and i fear what that will mean for how i raise my own children. should i have been a mother when i was young and an idealist? what will i have to offer by the time i feel ready to be one? hopefully not just skepticism and sarcasm.

324325;instagram;2018-09-30 12:41:27;FALSE;i have been struggling alot recently with my body
i will admit that i am being very harsh on myself and i have been judging myself a lot.
i don’t realise that i have given birth twice in three years and that does alot to one’s body.
when i look in the mirror i struggle with some things and people don’t see that but i do. this is where the war begins with self-confidence.

i might seem that i have got all under control but trust me guys it is not easy. by no means i am trying to say that i am portraying a different image but all i’m trying to do is fight with myself and come out better.

it is not easy to see yourself in the mirror and not like somethings and then dress up and go out and show the world that you can do it. but i want everyone to know that nobody is perfect and embrace yourself like you are.

stop thinking that you don’t look good enough and start doing what you think you can’t do.  @annakhan25 is the one who constantly push me to challenge myself and be comfortable in my own skin. this picture here i tried to push myself and not think about how i think i look.
love yourself girls and spread the same love to everyone else.

column1: 324346;instagram;2018-09-30 11:51:21;FALSE;believe women believe women believe women #triggerwarning i was raped 14 years ago. i never came forward. i still don’t feel like talking about it so y’all aren’t going to get the story. i 110% don’t feel like confronting my rapist. lol if you think he deserves justice. sadly
column2: justice doesn’t exist. if you are a person who doesn’t understand why a woman would wait...maybe just understand that you don’t need to understand...just believe her... and if you’re a woman who’s been lucky enough to have never been raped do not presume you would come forward straight away because some deep psychological shit is going to happen to you while you’re being raped and you really don’t know what you’ll do afterwards. . .(and i feel as i’m writing this that there are people that won’t believe me) and i’m sick to death of sexual assault being in the news...because it’s exhausting....and i’m tired of people bringing up kavanaugh to me because i’m a feminist and this is presumably an issue i’d want to rant about but talking about that current event makes me cry and clam up with nothing to say...for no conscious reason at all
column3: it’s called a trigger...and let me tell y’all it’s truly taking all the bravery i have to share even this much. and i’m dreading family members telling me that they’re sorry i was raped. and i’m dreading family members asking why i didn’t tell them. so maybe just don’t bother me about this face to face unless you’ve been raped too and want to share your story with me because i can tell you that sharing does help and it’s you that i’m here for. and at this point and time this is all the activism i can muster. i wish i was strong enough and healed enough and brave enough to do more. #metoo;;en;#triggerwarning

column1: je hoeft je niet meer te verstoppen.
het is tijd om het verdriet uit t verleden om te turnen in iets krachtigs moois.
niet meer bang zijn voor afstraffing.
niet meer je schuldig voelen omdat je het misschien op jezelf hebt afgeroepen.
waar mannen nog niet altijd onze kwetsbaarheid en kracht tegelijkertijd begrijpen.
we leven in een maatschappij waarin we elkaars vrouwelijke kracht vaak als een bedreiging zien in plaats van een verrijking.
we leven in een wereld vol oordelen en veroordelen.
we leven in een wereld waar grenzen zijn vervaagd en kei hard oordelen worden uitgesproken als we onze grenzen wel aangeven. .
oordeel niet meer over de ander.
laat een vrouw vol vrouw zijn.
met totaal respect voor ieders grenzen.
waar geen kei harde ja hoeft te worden gegeven.
waarin direct al duidelijk is dat je niemand zomaar mag aanraken.
waarin we open staan voor ieders verhaal.
waarin ieder #metoo verhaal super serieus wordt genomen.
waarin we niet meer bagataliseren als we onze grenzen aangeven.
of waarin onze verhalen uit t verleden loskomen.
iedere verkrachting of aanranding is er een.
ieder geluid laat zien dat t anders moet.
wat anderen ook zeggen of vinden.
laten we verhalen gaan schrijven hoe t anders kan. in plaats van vrouwen te veroordelen die hun mond open doen. .
we moeten onze kinderen weer leren wat grenzen zijn.
we moeten weer leren wat verbinding is.
we moeten de oordelen en veroordelingen over onszelf helen.
we moeten liever worden naar welke vrouw dan ook.
en elkaars grenzen en nee’s gaan accepteren. .
juist ook wij als vrouwen onder elkaar. waar we zo hard zijn. en vaak grenzen zo persoonlijk aantrekken.
we hebben nog zoveel te leren.
we hebben nog zoveel te veranderen.

column2: waar mannen nog niet altijd onze kwetsbaarheid en kracht tegelijkeijd begrijpen . . leven een maatschappij waarin elkaars vrouwelijke kracht vaak als een bedreiging zien plaats van een verrijking . . leven een wereld vol oordelen en veroordelen . . leven een wereld waar grenzen zijn vervaagd en kei hard oordelen worden uitgesproken als onze grenzen wel aangeven . . veroordeel jezelf niet meer . oordeel niet meer de ander . laat een vrouw vol vrouw zijn . een man vol man . . met totaal respect voor ieders grenzen . . waar geen kei harde ja hoeft te worden gegeven . een kei harde nee . . waarin direct al duidelijk dat je niemand zomaar mag aanraken . welke driften je ook hebt . . waarin open staan voor ieders verhaal . . waarin ieder verhaal super serieus wordt genomen . . waarin niet meer bagataliseren als onze grenzen aangeven . waarin onze verhalen uit verleden loskomen . . iedere verkrachting aanranding er een . ieder verhaal verdriet . ieder geluid laat zien dat anders moet . . veel je verhaal . wat anderen ook zeggen vinden . . jouw schuld niet . . laten verhalen gaan schrijven hoe anders kan. plaats van vrouwen te veroordelen die hun mond open doen . . moeten onze kinderen weer leren wat grenzen zijn . . moeten weer leren wat verbinding . . moeten de oordelen en veroordelingen onszelf helen . . moeten liever worden naar welke vrouw dan ook . . en elkaars grenzen en nee ’ gaan accepteren . . juist ook wij als vrouwen onder elkaar . waar zo hard zijn . en vaak grenzen zo persoonlijk aantrekken . . hebben nog zoveel te leren . . hebben nog zoveel te veranderen . . deel

column1: כי ילדה בת 13 חושבת יותר על הבושה החברתית מאשר על צדק.
כי היא מאוד רוצה להשתלב חברתית ומפחדת לא להתאקלם בשבט חדש.
כי זה נעשה לעיני כולם וזה מאוד הצחיק אותם.
כי יש תמונה שמתעדת את הרגע הזה והיא צוחקת בה מרוב מבוכה.
כי היא יודעת שרץ עליה סלאטשיימינג כבר הרבה זמן ועדיף לחכות שזה יעבור.
כי בגיל כזה קל לבלבל בין תקיפה מינית לבין אקט של תשומת לב מהמין השני.
כי היא מאוהבת בחבר שלו ולא רוצה להרוס כלום.

column1: un livre 📚 l’homme incertain de stéphanie chaillou... je ne parle que d’elle en ce moment (et de florent oiseau)
une citation📃 «la seule certitude que j’ai
column2: c’est d’être dans le doute» - pierre desproges (je l’aime)

column1: un (autre) ecrivain✒ florent oiseau (@florentoiseau)(intéressons-nous aux vivants)
un personnage de fiction🖌 robin - le coéquipier de batman (il a le même nom que moi mais il est plus agile)
un mot ✉ «félicité» (on l’emploie rarement ce mot)
une librairie 📗 la librairie du poussin.  c’est un camion librairie conduit par delphine poussin
column2: jeune femme courageuse et passionnée. elle parcourt l’essonne
column3: des endroits dénués de librairies et de bibliothèques
column4: et crée ainsi un lieu de proximité pour les habitants.

column1: un gros mot🤬 «merde» (ça se marie avec tout)
un endroit du monde🏝 la corse... pour la lumière
un hashtag ⚠ #metoo (car ce qui te concerne me concerne aussi)
une femme👧 goldie hawn - elle a mis en place un programme de méditation pour les enfants dans les écoles américaines
column2: pour leur apprendre à se relaxer et à se recentrer sur l’instant présent. elle a obtenu des résultats remarquables sur le bien-être des enfants.

column1: un souvenir ☎ le jour où anne carrière m’a téléphoné pour me dire qu’elle voulait publier mon roman roland est mort. j’étais en vacances en italie. le temps était magnifique. tout était trop beau pour être vrai.
quelques mots issus de tes romans😻 caniche. solitude. campari. désamour. corée. poème. chouquette.
une addiction 👿le vin rouge (montepulciano s’il vous plaît)  un compte  instagram📱 @melodiemcdaniel  melodie mcdaniel est une photographe - réalisatrice et je suis fan de son travail.
un sentiment😍 la joie - je sais
column2: ce n’est pas facile tous les jours.

column1: un film 📽 «lost in translation» de sofia coppola - ce film m’a inspiré pour écrire.
une chanson 🎶 «if i ever feel better» de phoenix.
le mot de la fin 🙋‍♂ c’est déjà fini ? je n’ai pas vu le temps passer. merci à tous les lecteurs et les lectrices de la bibliothèque de juju. c’est dommage de ne pas se voir plus souvent.

column4: but the charges where dropped because she was considered mentally unstable and unable to follow through with a trail.\\\\\\\\\

column2: we had sex once before and we had been dating for a few months. i kept saying no
column3: but he kept pushing. so i stopped saying no
column4: i said nothing and let my body go limp. i thought that because we were dating that i should just let him
column5: even if i didn’t want to
column6: i should just get it over with. i got pregnant and lost it three months later. i was bullied at school
column8: and i didn’t think anyone would be believe me.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\

column1: 324571;instagram;2018-09-30 07:03:30;FALSE;october is sexual violence awareness month & while it’s a pretty morbid topic it happens to people more than you may realise. 1 in 6 women & 1 in 20 men are sexually assaulted in australia from the age of 15. i’ve always shared my own journey & i know that many women don’t come forward or report sexual assaults to the police due to them accepting it as normal or because it’s expected of them from a friend
column3: boyfriend or husband. i’m here to remind you that nobody has the right to touch your body without your consent. consent is not - assumed
column5: implied or convinced. no means no
column6: being drunk & unable to say yes or reciprocate also means no
column7: not feeling like it means no as well. let’s respect each other & continue to show support to those who need it 💕 if you or someone you know has been affected by sexual assault please visit reachout.com or call 1800respect. #awareness #respect #iwillnotbesilent #metoo #standupspeakout;;en;#awareness

column1: its okay to not be okay !!
i've been struggling lately more than i normally do with my physical health not being flash my mental health has taken a dive also. but me being me tried to push on
column2: push through and smile through it all because sometimes it's easier just to smile and move in than to say the words i'm not okay.

column1: the past 9 months have given me so many wonderful blessings and some hard life lessons and moments where i thought i couldnt get through. but i am so very thankful to the people who stepped up never left my side who loved me none the less and made my life easier just by being in my life . being grateful for what you have is hard to see until something happens and you stop to actually look . so i encourage you to stop and think about who and what you are thankful for and tell them because they might not be here tomorrow ❤";;en;;;;;;0;;bodypositivepaige;🔥PAIGE🔥;;0;False;2;0;0;59;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/04b782f45dce0649f29f067384d4fd92/5D0D456C/t51.2885-15/e35/41657839_280540452783548_5254499309501403995_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"🌸warning long post🌸

column1: 324584;instagram;2018-09-30 06:26:06;FALSE;"luckily i don't watch a lot of tv and that in part can sometimes leave me uniformed. i am unfortunately getting caught up due to social media and the internet! i could hash tag #metoo or #rapeculture but what i want people to understand is this......this conversation hitting national news
column2: sparks apart of everyone who has been victimized. every victim on all sides much like the montagues and capulets are at a loss
column3: there  is no winners. every victim no matter how hard they try holds a piece of this trauma with them for the rest of their life. they become hyper vigilant and having national news like this reawakens this vigilance. it makes me happy to see people tell their story's because when we are silent it allows others to tell our story. much like the debates seen on tv.....this is rape culture. this debate is something that happens to every victim who speaks up. like two sides to a coin even a perpetrator is someone's kid.

column1: their is healing and triumph in being able to speak up for yourself or help others. please be patient and aware of the pain this conversation ignites in those around you. those who are speaking out are just a small percentage of victims strong enough to stand up. there are many more who have yet to learn to speak their peace. victims have one thing in common. while they come in all shapes sizes and genders....these people at their very core are the embodiment of beauty

column2: this was a gut-wrenching and personally traumatic point in history. for our country
column3: it has been a moment of reckoning that is long overdue."" my latest for @ranttmedia 👇 for survivors
column4: the ford-kavanaugh hearing was deeply personal! i’m a survivor of sexual assault. this entire process has been a roller coaster of emotion.

column1: if you’re a survivor stumbling through this week feeling like a shell-shocked soldier
column2: you’re not alone. the political drama surrounding the accusations from dr. blasey ford and the subsequent kavanaugh hearing has forced us all to relive moments in our lives we’ve tried very hard to forget. many survivors of sexual assault who had carefully crafted successful lives found ourselves with the demons of memory nipping at our heels this week
column3: threatening to overwhelm our equilibrium and force us out of silence. for many survivors like me
column4: this was a gut-wrenching and personally traumatic point in history. for our country
column5: it has been a moment of reckoning that is long overdue. our journey to this precipice didn’t happen when dr. christine blasey ford’s accusations surfaced earlier this month. it’s been happening for years. while the parallels to anita hill’s experience during the confirmation proceedings of clarence thomas are undeniable
column6: the rage from women lies much closer to the oval office. when donald trump was elected
column7: the sense of betrayal cut deep for survivors of sexual assault and harassment. our fellow americans had elevated someone who we saw as a sexual predator
column8: a man who threatened and showed violent tendencies
column9: and given him power over our lives. after the first few days of grief
column10: many women moved into a space of righteous indignation and rage. how dare they drag us back to the dark ages
column11: where we were at the mercy of powerful men who saw us as objects to be possessed instead of human beings and fellow citizens with unalienable rights.

column1: and it wasn’t just donald trump. it was his whole host of horrible ghouls and goblins the gop had brought along for the ride. despicable men who had spent most of their lives abusing positions of power and privilege. rob porter

324601;instagram;2018-09-30 06:18:15;FALSE;ironically, this time last year, i discovered an online blog of a (now) man that i dated in high school. he has a terminal illness & created a blog under his real name. he is married & is a father to a young daughter. although i’m not directly named, there are more than enough details that, if you knew me in high school, you know who he is talking about. this person essentially outed my awful emotional, sexual, & family history in cutting detail. the events he detailed happened in 1986-1987, the age of kavanaugh’s preppy bro coming of age culture. the discovery of this entry hobbled me. i lay on my couch, weeping. i was embarrassed about how i reacted: it was high school-who cares? but mark cared enough to write about a relationship he felt made him a man. and i cared. i cared because because i am a witness & survivor of intense emotional abuse. i am a witness & survivor of physical abuse. i live with depression & anxiety due to these events. i have made several attempts of suicide, including the time he chose to write about. 25 years+ of therapy, medication, & the love & support of a cadre of people, the most essential being my partner for nearly 30 years has softened the edges & most of all given me hope & belief that life is worth living & that trust is a precious thing. i haven’t spoken to mark in 30 years. i doubt that, outside of an apology i left on his blog, i ever will. i have struggled through anger, embarrassment, & shame for years. and still do. with lesser intensity, but it's still there, bubbling under an aging skin of a person still trying to make sense of her past & look forward, with a semblance of positive expectancy. as i said a year ago, for those for those of you in my social media sphere, if i have hurt through words and actions, i am sorry. and i say that sincerity & with, most of all, love. and finally, my social media is my brave space. it is my safe space. if you cannot respect me & my history as an imperfect friend, woman, human being, and especially child, i will say this in the most authentically me way possible: step the fuck off of here & leave me alone. #project365 #day273 #metoo #ibelievechristineblaseyford #fuckbrettkavanaugh;;en;#project365, #day273, #metoo, #ibelievechristineblaseyford, column1: 324622;instagram;2018-09-28 03:28:49;FALSE;"🚨warning- this post could potentially be triggering to those who have been affected by sexual assault or abuse in some way or form  and have deeply rooted trauma in their past. anyone else sharing their stories should post this warning as well.🚨
watching the kavanaugh hearing has lead me (and i’m sure many others) to recount buried memories from many years ago of being pressured sexually into something unwanted.

reading old journal entries recently i realized i am glad that i wrote it down. if i had not written it down these memories would have been blocked out of my mind completely. reading them today i realized back then i was unsure of what had actually happened.
just because someone doesn’t speak up immediately when something occurs doesn’t mean that it never happened. it should not be degraded or disregarded because of how many years have passed by.
bad behavior is bad behavior. no means no. stop means stop. it’s hard to open up and be vulnerable but i know i’m not alone here and shouldn’t feel embarrassed or ashamed to share this.
dr. christine blasey ford was very brave today to do something so scary in a very public way and #ibelieveher ... #stopkavanaugh #metoo #believesurvivors #webelieveyou";;en;#ibelieveher

column1: 324647;instagram;2018-09-30 05:36:02;FALSE;"fathers and men who don’t know what to do with the current climate of women in pain
column2: what do you do to protect and teach your daughters/sons/children?

column1: don’t tell them you’ll rage and pummel and hunt and kill. they will fear for their boyfriend or friend or status or circle. they will keep secrets. they will fear far more and be too unsure of what they can prove to justify the seemingly overwhelming backlash. especially if there is no evidence

sit with your daughters and sons. be okay with silence. be okay with time passing. let comfort grow. let conversation arise as they wonder. let them ask and imagine and trust and grow with you in a place with no deadlines and no sense of results. let there be room.
noble men who are open and ready to understand and connect
column2: thank you. your children and others’ children want a place to go. you can be that place and that example and that ideal of respect and stillness and strength.

column1: to the men who are listening and who have never had reason to fear but believe that women are afraid all the time and think that is wrong
column2: thank you for bridging that divide and defending women in that lonely gulf.

column1: sometimes there is no action to take. sometimes it’s just love and being okay sitting with sad things. no one can fix these things
column2: but we can be there and be in no rush and love above all.

column1: in recent years much of my reading has been focused on ""fun"" reads or ""useful"" reads
column2: such as books about business or self growth. i realized i've somewhat neglected books like this one
column3: which i first read in high school. books that are not the easiest to read
column4: but are full of philosophy and wisdom and truth.

column2: i've been spending a lot of time thinking about the testimonies of dr. blasey ford and judge kavanaugh
column3: and the politics and discussion around them. i've had some interesting conversations
column4: and it has reiterated to me the importance of truly thinking about and discussing difficult topics
column5: rather than just reading about them or repeating what you've heard. in times like these when complex issues are constantly being condensed into catchy headlines
column6: let us take the time to not only consume the information and opinion surrounding us
column7: but to form our own ideas and share them with those we know.

column1: 324655;instagram;2018-09-30 05:41:16;FALSE;i was very fortunate tonight to watch a rally for someone i’d been curious about. this is going to be my first year voting and i’ve been trying to do research on who i’ll vote for an why. i got to hear words of hope spoken as you see at most political rallies. but something was very incredible hearing beto speak. i heard something that you rarely hear from politicians. change being talked about without parties. beto addressed no matter what party you were from
column2: if you were there tonight you were in the right place. these past two years have been the wild west for politics. as a newly 18 (now 19) year old i’ve watched many things happen and change. for the worse a lot. i’ve watched the #metoo movement rise and shine a glimmer of hope for every woman like me who’s experienced the patriarchal injustice that is sexual assault. i’ve watched the country shed tears for separated families and children locked in cages. i’ve seen the supreme court justice nominee being accused of what i’m afraid every time i walk down a dark street. and i’ve watched many deny that all those things have any merit.  these things have made me realize so much. tonight
column4: the man i have a cat named after
column5: sing “if you don’t like who’s in office
column6: vote them out.” and i think that sums up what i’ve learned from all of this. people are cruel
column7: and it horribly affects so many. but the only way to change any of that is to stand up

column1: 324657;instagram;2018-09-28 07:03:44;FALSE;"ever since the larry nassar case i’ve wanted to publicly speak out about my experience with sexual assault. i’ve wanted to name my abuser
column2: maybe even report him and hopefully find some closure in that
column3: yet still i’m not completely ready. i was 8 years old the first time it happened
column4: it has been 10 years since i’ve escaped that scary part of my life
column5: but i’m still not ready. for two years of my childhood i was terrified
column7: and ashamed about something that a man decided to do to me. how absurd is it that we can’t help but feel ashamed because someone else assaulted us? i just started to accept that it ever even happened this past year. those who have never faced this sort of trauma may not understand it
column8: but simply accepting the fact that something like this happened to you is hard enough
column9: let alone saying the words out loud for others to hear. for some reason
column10: though it’s no ones fault but your assaulters
column11: you feel guilt and shame as if you could have anticipated and prevented it from happening. talking about it and reporting it may in some cases mean justice
column12: but in most cases it means facing your own and others judgement
column13: the scary truth that people may not believe you
column14: reliving the incident over and over
column15: the fear of looking like an attention seeker. the assault alone is terrifying but what comes after is almost worse. i understand why dr. ford didn’t report up until now

column1: i send my love and support to anyone who has ever had to live through the terrifying reality that is sexual assault. remember

column1: never silent. i am really very open about the birth trauma i experienced. possibly too much. sometimes i wonder if i should be 'protecting' myself more... if anyone asks me about o's birth i tell them the truth. i don't go into the details unless they seem interested
column2: but i do say it was awful. often people seem like they don't know what to say. that's okay i guess. if i'm talking to a pregnant woman i mellow out my story and just say something like 'i had a bad time
column3: but you don't need to hear about that'. if she asked more though
column4: i would probably tell her. adults can decide for themselves what they do / don't want to hear or read. sometimes i wonder if still talking about my trauma over 2 years later makes people think i should get over it or that i'm after sympathy. i'm not. and i wouldn't like them to be thinking that. but i'm not going to shut up about it. it happened to me. it was awful. i think about it a lot. if someone asks how i am and they don't really want to hear the truth

column1: i am a survivor of multiple accounts of rape.
i am a survivor of sexual abuse.
i am a survivor of my mental illness.
i was raped three times by three different men in 2009. i was 14.
i was sexually assaulted & raped by a 27 year old male when i was 16.
i was sexually assaulted several times by an ex boyfriend. he also raped & sodomised me under the influence.

column2: i was guilt tripped by men on tinder to have sex with them. this is not rape but this is also very wrong to do.

column1: i have never been comfortable sexually until my current husband & even my past experiences still catch up to me. my husband is the only man i have ever been with where i feel safe. i don’t feel pressured. it is my body & he respects it.
these are my stories. stories i am now deciding to share with everyone. i haven’t told anyone these.
you’re wondering why i did report? why i didn’t tell an adult? because i’ve been taught through media
column3: how i saw men treat women that women belonged to men. i did not know that what happened was horribly wrong & that i had options to report. it has only been recently that i’ve come to terms with what has happened to me. i felt alone & isolated in my situations because consent had never been talked about.

column1: i realize i was intoxicated for all of them but i don’t fucking care. it shouldn’t have happened. instead they should’ve wrapped me up in a blanket & let me sleep it off. they should’ve comforted me
column2: not taken advantage of my vulnerability. these men are predators. they knew what they they were doing.

column1: i have a voice & i am going to use it. if any of you want to share your stories
column3: i encourage you to do so. i am here for you.";;en;#whyididntreport

column4: he swung wildly in my direction and connected with my chest. i gasped for breath
column5: instantly aware of the room and the man deeply entrenched in his subconscious flash back fighting for his life. i scrambled to escape his reach but before i could
column6: he grabbed my arm and pinned me down
column7: wrapping his hands tightly around my throat
column8: the fire in his eyes something that could be felt as well as seen in the dim light. at that moment i threw all of my strength into fighting for my life. i clawed at his hands

column1: 324745;instagram;2018-09-30 04:07:17;FALSE;"i am deeply touched by the courage dr. ford displayed this week by sharing her story in front of our entire nation. not to mention her courage in agreeing to relive this surely traumatic event by participating in an fbi investigation.
there are so few words to say to describe the grief and anger i share with so many of my sisters who have been raped or sexually assaulted
column2: and subdued into silence. this movement is beyond powerful. national sexual assault hotline calls have increased 147% since her testimony and women are gradually opening up to voice their stories.
i stood at the foot of a waterfall and allowed the earth to ground me
column3: to hold me while i sat with this deep pain in my belly. this is an injustice for all women. there are two things i feel called to share with you.

column2: serious fbi investigation. it should not be limited to one week. the fbi should have a reasonable amount of time to do its job. add your name to the petition in my bio link if you agree.

column1: 2) i'm offering three free sessions for women who are feeling triggered by the events of this week. this is on a first come
column2: first serve basis. please message me if you're interested.

column1: 324751;instagram;2018-09-30 04:11:24;FALSE;"i’m not going to hide any longer. i’m not going to keep quiet for one more day. i’m not going to suppress my feelings towards this kavanaugh-ford court case for fear of a backlash or disapproval from those who simply can’t understand. i never participate in politics
column2: but today i can’t hold back.

column1: unfortunately many of the women who watch this case from their couch can understand the agonizing fear and discomfort and terrorizing trauma that ms. ford proclaimed to the supreme court this week. and i was one of them.
the overwhelming majority of men staring her down
column2: the astronomical amount of listeners in the audience and around the world
column3: including her family and loved ones and those who would undoubtedly change the way they see a once profound woman now in a fragile state revealing details about her past
column4: peeling off layers of security to unleash bare secrecy about an event that took away a lot from her. and i can’t say what it was exactly that this man took
column5: but i knew it was something
column6: because i lost it once too.

column2: to strip away the courage of hiding a shameful secret
column3: is something i’ve never had the balls to ever dream of doing... until now.

column1: i was a victim of rape at 20 years old.
on a remote island off the coast of costa rica
column3: i was  without the ability to escape or run or scream or seek help

column1: i share this ugly truth for every other motive but that of seeking sympathy. that is not my motive. i simply share this story and standpoint on a media-driven
column2: politically saturated account to hopefully help someone somewhere someday  realize that it’s okay to speak about sexual violence. it’s okay to talk about “the forbidden.” it’s okay to sink in the discomfort of presenting a punishing past. to come forth and set it free is as therapeutic as a handful of pharmaceutical antidepressants. it’s as liberating as screaming across the ocean. it’s as terrifying (yet rewarding) as standing before thousands of judicial professionals to justify a wrongdoing. for me
column3: it’s not about male supremacy. it’s about facing the fear of sexual violence. #metoo";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;yogajesss;⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀Jessica Melvin;;0;False;7;0;0;40;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/bf4d32867e4c07b3574390e2b86099f3/5D16D74B/t51.2885-15/e35/41549449_521508334989379_7625789468908854675_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i’m not going to hide any longer. i’m not going to keep quiet for one more day. i’m not going to suppress my feelings towards this kavanaugh-ford court case for fear of a backlash or disapproval from those who simply can’t understand. i never participate in politics

column1: as a survivor of sexual assault
column2: i’m feeling all the feelings right now. rage. sadness. disbelief. rage. numbness. cynicism. triggered af. white hot rage. it feels like our stories don’t matter
column4: because even when one of us gets up and bravely delves into every tiny detail of what happened for hours on end in front of millions of people
column5: it’s not enough to sway the men in power. and truly
column6: we *don’t* matter to those men; we never did. the only thing that matters to them is holding onto their power and privilege—including power over the bodies of women and other marginalized people—and accumulating more of it.

column1: but even if we don’t matter to them
column2: we still matter to the world. we still matter to anyone with a moral compass
column3: a shred of decency. we still matter to history. because generations from now
column4: people are going to look back and see this and the whole #metoo and #timesup movement as a turning point
column5: a moment when a powerful wave of survivors shook off the shame and rose up to tell our stories. the first woman president of the united states
column7: was watching those hearings and feeling a growing call to action. the stories that survivors have been telling these past few years matter. we still matter. you still matter.

column1: so please take care of yourself
column2: and treat yourself like you matter. you deserve to eat
column5: to leave the house if you feel ready. you deserve to lie in bed all day if that’s what you need. and then
column7: you deserve to take to the streets in protest
column8: and to fight back at the polls in november. you deserve to have your voice heard
column9: because it matters. you deserve to take up space

column1: 324764;instagram;2018-09-27 02:35:30;FALSE;"#fbpo = for black people only. self-explanatory but for those who aren’t black & are eager to provide commentary…don’t. this ain't for you. •
#houstonwehaveaproblem! as if it weren’t disheartening enough that women are now more discouraged to come forward
column2: one of the most frustrating thing about all this is how ppl don’t get why white men aren’t punished the same way in a system built on white supremacy. the system is designed to protect them. fight the system. but please don’t defend the criminals. i just needed to go on record because y’all cousins are getting on my nerves!

column1: edit 09/30/18: non-blacks keep pointing out that this issue surpasses race and for that
column2: there are three things i’d like to point out: 1. they are correct. 2. you didn’t follow instructions. and 3. this is a black ppl only post for a reason and since i wasn’t clear
column3: let me be crystal clear.  bill cosby represents something unique to the black community. he was something we had never seen in tv or in media in general. and black doctor with his lawyer wife whose storylines weren’t centered around being black. bill cosby inspired generations by seeing themselves and motivated black youth to attend black colleges and universities. he was a media mogul with multiple shows he was producing or starring in. a black man was the representation of “america’s dad” in a world that had portrayed black men as anything other than. he was a father to many of us whose fathers had been snatched by the legal system or the war on drugs (which worked hand and hand). so the disgust and/or defense of cosby means something different to our community...something a non-black wouldn’t understand. and if you’re non-black

324775;instagram;2018-09-30 03:35:46;FALSE;i was one of the first women at the beginning to warn people around me why the #metoo movement was also a pb. i had harsh comments from other women telling me i was playing against them and i was not a feminist.

i am a feminist and as you know i had enough abusive experiences in my life to talk about the real deal... i could play that victim blaming shaming but i don't... why i don't because i am a real feminist i seek equality of gender not  man hater ... for me the #metoo movement is about man hating it is not about feminism it is about having the power in another hand (from men to women) and blaming & shaming the other sex to get them down (as they did to us) to change that. in another words
column2: using the same methods as them and being as weak as them.

column1: in my opinion that is absolutely wrong!

if you are abused by someone you know that is a personality disorder problem so they consider themselves as a victim already.  so in doing that blaming shaming of the #metoo you wil just reinforce the problem instead of curing it.

the real power is about being strong and lifting the situation in working out the difference and understand each other! and educate educate and educate... the real power is about finding a global approach (legal medical psychological and spiritual) to cure this abuse problem.
we are the victims if we want to play that victim role ... but we can be so much better than that ... don't you think?

column1: 324804;instagram;2018-09-30 03:07:32;FALSE;"unless you’ve been living under a rock you know the topic of sexual assault is in the news again. which means your feed is probably flooded with “opinions” of people who don’t really know much (or anything) about sexual assault or trauma or the criminal justice system.

i’m sharing a post i read recently from a victim of sexual assault who writes about her experience as someone who immediately came forward and about others who choose not to come forward right away. i admire her strength and honesty and vulnerability. i hope if you or someone you know doesn’t quite understand why a victim might not come forward right away this post will help shed some light (see insta story). i also want to clarify something else that i see coming up all the time - the idea that when it comes to sexual assault we just can’t weigh in or lend support to victims or don’t know until or unless an accused person is convicted in court. the presumption of innocence is a basic and fundamental principle of law here in canada. and i believe in it wholeheartedly. but lack of proof beyond a reasonable doubt in a criminal court room is not the same thing as factual innocence. there is a reason we do not say “you are innocent” and instead say you are “not guilty”. the two are not the same thing.

if a friend of yours came to you and said they were the victim of a robbery would your first reaction be to ask them if their purse was too flashy? or what street they were walking down? or if they ran away or shouted when they were being attacked? or if they had been drinking ... because no one can really know what they are talking about if they have had a drink or two
column2: you know. or if they told the first person they saw? and did they cry? like really
column3: really hard? for the vast majority of people the answer is no; these thoughts wouldn’t even enter your mind because you would be too busy expressing your concern and wanting to hear their truth. but that’s not the case for how society generally responds to victims of sexual assault. victims of sexual assault are scrutinized to a degree victims of other offences are not and criticized for many things victims of other offences are not. column1: 324829;instagram;2018-09-30 03:16:35;FALSE;"this was supposed to be just another pretty wildlife picture.
i’ve been thinking to myself that others have said it better
column2: that one more voice and one more opinion won’t change things
column3: that i don’t have a personal story to share
column4: so why bother making waves? why bother telling people things they refuse to hear? why bother
column5: when i know full well that some of you will judge my opinions harshly?

column1: and then i thought of the survivors i know. survivors of sexual violence. (the capitalization is to bring home the violent bit). their experiences affected each of them in different ways. to my knowledge
column2: most of them did not speak out immediately after their assaults. some of these fine people have now publicly shared their stories. some still have not and may never share their stories. an over-arching theme
column4: is fear. people are afraid of the consequences of speaking out about the sexual violence that is committed against them. what kind of world do we live in that
column5: instead of supporting those who have been attacked
column6: we judge them for it?! people are afraid to speak out because they’ll be shamed
column7: they’ll be told they were “asking for it” because of their clothing or because they’ve consumed alcohol or because of their sexual orientation or gender identity. (by the way
column8: if your instinct isn’t to get physically ill when you hear a rape victim be told that bullshit
column11: you still don’t find victim-blaming horrific
column12: kindly remove yourself from my vicinity.) so then
column13: why bother reporting sexual violence? why bother talking about it openly? why
column16: survivors are faced with the fact that a vast majority of perpetrators will not go to jail or prison? why am i bothering to talk to you about the beautiful people i know who have been affected?

column1: because i am absolutely fucking enraged
because you still refuse to believe women
because when it’s a woman’s word against a man’s you default to believing the man. that is why.

column4: one long battle of ptsd and fighting daily to make it to the next... so if you find yourself shut down
column11: without guilt. without shame - do what you need to do to distract
column13: care for and rest your whole self. because after all its not our silence thats been the problem.

column1: 324873;instagram;2018-09-30 02:18:52;FALSE;warning this is my own story of assault. i was a freshman in high school and in eugene oregon
column2: a guy named grant was in college and liked me. i liked that he was in college and older and honestly i was curious. he asked me to come to a frat party and i did. i think i went alone i’m not sure.  i don’t remember the details of how i got there or when it was. i drank it was a fun party. he asked me to come to his room. i did. we had sex and i didn’t want to but i suffered in silence because i was afraid and i kept telling myself i put myself there what did i expect. he was violent it was painful.  i never told anyone. honestly i just blamed myself.  i stuffed that experience so deep that i didn’t even remember it until recently.  it came flooding back to me. i am a tough person and i was a tough kid but i was a young girl. i thought this was my fault.  i now know it wasn’t and i forgive myself and i will do everything i can to protect my girls from the same fate. the shift is upon us and we can no longer think we can’t say no or think that predatory behavior is ok even when we are curious. #metoo #timesup;;en;#metoo

column1: and why we do what we do
but while they’re paying so much attention
from broken dreams to broken hearts
but too afraid to lean towards tomorrow.
with low self-esteem and put downs
we can’t help but to ask why
friends lost and loved ones gone
we wonder what the future brings
we wonder how we can be strong
still they wonder why we act the way we act
but how can we be so generous
with all of the tears and times of pain
it seems we won’t get far
unless we take time to try
and get rid of our invisible scars.

column1: 324901;instagram;2018-09-30 02:32:56;FALSE;"this is a quick note to the nice guy at the checkout counter
column2: and the friendly woman behind me in line. she asked about my day
column3: i asked about hers. she sang her husband's praises-- he's taking care of the kids and cooking dinner while she gets last-minute groceries and takes a break because it's been a day. i say it's so nice to have that kind of support. thank god for her husband
column4: she says. thank god for all men. all men are good men
column5: she says. the check out guy thanks her-- it's good to hear that today. and now that i am not frozen in a nice smile of ""pleasejustgetmethefuckawayfromthesemanworshipingpeoplewhodontcareaboutwomensbasicsafetyandconstantreality
column6: here is what i wish i'd said in response: (trigger warning).

column1: i know some good men. but every woman that i have ever known has had multiple experiences of being harassed
column5: coerced or violently raped. and i'm tired of worrying that men feel bad when women talk about the fact that we live in a society that protects rapists and abusers at the expense of women and children. may your god bless you both with compassion that centers on lived experiences outside your own. #enough #metoo #butistillfreeze #andrunaway and it took me half an hour alone in my car to find these words. #believesurvivors #andthenfuckoff #stopkavanaugh #stillinflightmode #alltheadrenalinemakingmenauseous #youmattertomenomatterwhathedid";;en;#enough

column6: but it definitely made going to work scary. i didn't think anyone would believe me

column1: last night i dreamed i was sitting bedside waiting for someone to die
loved ones i've never met lined the halls outside the room in metal chairs.
i went home in the interim.
began to pack up my house. where we were moving
i know you feel it at some level too.
a move. a shift. an opening.
i listen as you open all the windows.
but it scares the shit out of me.

column1: 324941;instagram;2018-09-30 02:06:43;FALSE;"這個禮拜聽了一堂有關反對性騷擾/暴力的”me too”運動的介紹，而且是科部大晨會的特殊演講；
對於這樣的議題在醫院能夠受到重視，著實覺得意外也驚喜。 .
可能因為給人比較強悍的形象，自己從沒有遇過肢體上的騷擾；
但即使身處性別概念相對進步的環境，生活周遭仍能夠看見不少帶有性意味的言語騷擾、歧視與玩笑。
「因為只是幾句白目的話，跟他計較反而浪費時間」；
即使不舒服，大多數時候我們也就這樣忽略、忍了下來。
但我們都知道，世界上有很多人並不是這麼的幸運——
她們每天遭遇的並不只是「幾句話」，卻還是得面對社會對她們「為大局相忍」的期待。
而這一忍，往往就是放在心裡再也說不出口，讓加害者得寸進尺。
無論對於女性或男性，我們都有義務共同打造一個讓每個人都能感到自在且安全的環境。
即使不是當事人，我們也應該去警覺與幫助這樣的狀況。 .
很想跟在這世界上遭遇過性騷擾、無論言語或肢體暴力，卻因為現實被社會噤聲的人們說聲：辛苦了。
我很幸運，出生在一個不會要女孩子忍耐的家庭；
而我真的很希望，沒有人要因為非自己所願的事而忍耐的那一天，能夠快點到來。

because nobody’s out in this work of making the world a better place for everyone to feel safe and comfortable. .  #metoo #metoomovement #nomore #sexual #harrassment #love #woman #womenpower";;en;#metoo

column2: but this week has been tough af
column3: & seeing how dr. christine blasey ford can put literally everything on the line to protect her country & empower survivors
column4: i feel now that i can come forward

column1: i am a survivor of sexual assault.
what happened to me was not my fault. it never was. i don’t need to tell you what happened. i don’t need to tell you that after he did what he did to me
column2: he threatened me. i don’t need to tell you how he told me not to tell anyone. i don’t need to tell you how i lost friends because they victim-blamed me or defended him as a character witness in someone else’s hearing. i dont need to tell you how the title ix coordinator thought reading the definition of consent to him would be enough. i don’t need to tell you that i was wearing tye-dye
column4: and a monsters university baseball cap. but i tell you because i need you to understand why you need to believe survivors & support them & stand up for them.

column1: this is why survivors don’t come forward. threat. fear. blame. because we don’t get believed again & again. because we don’t get justice. again & again.
i carried shame about what happened to me for a long time. but i realized that the shame is not for me to carry
column2: but for the abusers to carry. i should not be ashamed. i should be proud. because look at how strong i am. look at my resilience. i survived. do you have any idea how freakin miraculous that is?

column1: it’s not just dr. ford that made me want to come forward. it’s the inspiration of so many incredible survivors that shared their stories too (shoutouts to @solsister24 @millsburger @vigilannie_ ) who have supported me endlessly. it’s an amazing feeling to have best friends who you look up to who also look up to you. i want to continue to make you proud.

i hope that sharing this part of my identity ends some stigma around sexual assault. i hope it provides survivors with courage. i hope it creates understanding. we need to stop looking at sexual assault as a rare thing. someone close to you has experienced it. there’s so damn many of us. let’s keep fighting until there’s none of us.";;en;;@solsister24

column2: i am a survivor. (sorry i forgot to post this) also
column3: i never reported my encounter because i was afraid of police at the time (but that is a while other story because of parental abuse growing up that resulted to police) i couldn’t report it also because i believed i wouldn’t be listened to so i only told my father and my cousins. i never spoke or saw the guy ever again. i applaud those brave women who report their answers years later but i personally couldn’t because i could never ever put myself in the same situation in seeing that man again. the night he molested me was the night i was walking with him and his dogs at 8pm during the early winter. after walking to the baseball park
column4: i was sitting down. he sat next to me
column5: then grabbed me and put me on his lap (i was 112lbs at the times) *again i was in 12th grade in 2012*  he then proceeds to put his hand on my crotch. i shoved him away and got up and jumped the fence so fast and ran to a trusted adult i could tell. #wiccan #pagan #feminism #metoo #sexualabuse #feministwitch #noncontensental #rapeculture #molestationsurvivor #molestationawareness;;en;#wiccan

column3: att jag trodde att jag skulle bli allvarligt skadad. men jag berättade aldrig för någon. jag fick ju skylla mig själv. hade jag inte bråkat så hade inget hänt. detta mönster har genomsyrat hela mitt liv. jag har alltid lagt skulden på mig själv. hos mamma var jag ju ""ett argt barn"". hade jag inte varit det så hade inget behövt hända.
jag gjorde inte på rätt sätt. samma beteende och tankesätt senare vid de sexuella övergreppen. självklart var det mitt eget fel. jag räckte inte till som flickvän
column4: jag var ju såklart tvungen att ställa upp och om jag inte ställde upp fick jag såklart ta konsekvenserna. när det kommer till min mammas framförallt psykiska misshandel så hade jag perioder där jag ifrågasatte henne. men jag lärde mig snabbt att det gav enorma konsekvenser för mig så jag slutade ifrågasätta helt enkelt. idag försöker jag tänka och komma ihåg att det är/var inte mitt fel. jag ska inte skämmas eller ta på mig skulden för vad dessa människor utsatte mig för. skulden ligger hos dem. men ändå... det är svårt. tanken ""jag borde"" finns där så ofta. hur kommer det sig att man automatiskt lägger skulden på sig själv utan att någon sagt att det är ens eget fel. och hur kommer man ur skuld och skam känslorna? #komplexptsd #trauma #barnmisshandel #psykiskmisshandel #sexuellaövergrepp #metoo #skuldochskam #bryttabun";;en;#komplexptsd

column1: 324962;instagram;2018-09-30 01:45:49;FALSE;"tell me one thing you're grateful for. i'll tell you about a few. .

column2: i'm grateful to have been heard. sharing my #metoo story was the hardest thing i did in my entire life. i shared it multiple times before someone heard me. before someone told me that i wasn't crazy. before someone told me that it was not my fault. before someone believed me. before someone told me that i was not just a heartbroken girl. before someone said ""me too"" to me. you see this face? it wasn't always like this. i’ve noticed how much my face has changed over the last year. i don’t see the same scream i used to see before to be heard somehow. or seen somehow. i see me. just me. as i am.
i grateful for my heart. and
column4: does it get overwhelming. i live with a roller coaster of emotions every single day. and i am so grateful for that. because it means that i am human. that i can feel with and for others. that i can be mindful of my own self.

column2: i am grateful for each and every one of you who is still choosing to walk this journey with me. mind platter and the nectar of pain would not be the same without you.

column3: please take us off your list. why would i send money to help children of the people in american society who need it the least? ​​.

column1: ​​today a letter from will’s all-boys prep school alma mater came in the mail. my husband is a good man whom i would be hard pressed to believe ever sexually assaulted anyone
column2: even unintentionally. but he admits that he has behaved in ways he feels compelled now
column4: to apologize for. he is not surprised
column6: by the stories of sexism fueled by elite east coast schools surfacing via the kavanaugh hearings: he encountered multiple bretts in his years at “gillie tech” as his friends affectionately call it.

column1: one thing that really pains and puzzles me is my seemingly progressive
column2: leftist friends who send their kids to private schools
column3: perpetuating the very inequality they daily lament. if i had kids now
column4: even if i could afford to send them to private schools
column5: i wouldn’t. i believe that strong public education is essential to a functioning democracy
column8: won’t work unless we are all equal participants in it. ​​i am the product of an entire lifetime of public education in small
column9: rural places with few resources and hold my own every day with people from my husband and kavanaugh’s elite backgrounds. public education worked just fine for me. ​​on the entitlement and sexism fostered at these exclusive educational institutions
column12: writes in an op-ed for usatoday:

column4: which meant we had to protect ourselves against boys. in essence
column5: we could socialize with the boys in our prep school circles
column6: but it was our responsibility to control the boys because they could not be relied upon or expected to control themselves. any failure in that department was our shame alone. and alone we carried it.”

column1: 324994;instagram;2018-09-30 01:22:06;FALSE;i don’t talk much of my own #metoo experience. never on social media. it’s different and painful and sensitive for every person who has experienced someone crossing our private boundaries. but i do have a few things that i’m preparing to say. i think it’s important. if #drchristineblaseyford & #anitahill’s testimonies were nothing else
column2: they’re a clear siren to those of us who have our own story to use our voice & speak up in public to possibly prevent others from experiencing any type of similar private shame. even if our voices shake. even if the memory that’s indelible in the hippocampus brings us back to the age we were when the trauma happened. more to say later. i’m almost ready to share. don’t quite have the words. in the meantime

column1: 324998;instagram;2018-09-30 01:22:56;FALSE;and now what? while we are angry as hell about everything that deserves it
column3: for it does us no good. we must continue to put pressure on our senators to do the right thing
column4: push the #metoo & #believesurvivors movement ahead with all our might
column5: and get out the vote (don’t just vote but encourage and help others to vote as well). but we also need to slow down sometimes
column6: take a break from the news and social media
column7: and just look around. what are you grateful for as you notice the myriad hues of green on a single leaf? a billowing white cloud on a sunny day? i’m so not into the idea of good vibes only. it is actually really annoying. there’s an entire spectrum of emotions inside all of us. and it would be unhealthy to not allow ourselves to feel each of them all the way to their inner depths. just as we cannot live in happiness and contentment at all times (if you are so enlightened
column9: but also i hope you’re still voting)
column10: it’s also detrimental to boil our souls in rage and anger all the time. feeling mad helps us recognize what we are afraid of and what we are willing to fight for. letting ourselves feel happiness and peace
column11: to check in with nature and our mind beyond the chatter
column12: these are calming tools that will also help us fight the good fight.;;en;#metoo
